    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-04-05T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-04-05T11:00:00-05:00" n="757"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d757">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.94/152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Phillips</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-04-05T18:00:00+02:00"
                            >April 5, 1941—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 7:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>[469.] Embassy’s 456 and 457, April 4.<note n="42" xml:id="d757fn42">Neither
                        printed.</note> I have learned on the best authority that during his
                    conversations with the Pope and the <pb facs="0939" n="931" xml:id="pg_931"/>
                    Cardinal Secretary of State Matsuoka stressed the following points: (1) In
                    China, Japan was conducting a campaign against communism, not a war against the
                    Chinese people, (2) an extension and prolongation of the European war could only
                    favor the cause of communism, (3) Japan had no desire to be drawn into this
                    war.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Berlin.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
